    <segment id="1" parent="23" relname="circumstance">
When I read this article,</segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="24" relname="span"> it made me think of something that happened at work recently.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="25" relname="span">  
A programmer who &quot;knew what the user wanted&quot; created a web page for payroll and 
other type of file submissions to the bank.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="10" relname="concession">  He put security on the files,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="18" relname="span"> but there was no 
security if one went through the web page to submit the files to the bank.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="15" relname="span">  What 
happened was that a user who didn&apos;t have access to the payroll file was going through 
the web page and accidentially hitting the payroll submission button to submit the file.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="22" relname="span">  
Payroll was being submitted twice to the bank.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="20" relname="span">  What this tells me is that the users reallly 
needed protection from errors.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="17" relname="conjunction">  The users were never exposed to the web page prior to 
being put in production,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="17" relname="conjunction"> and the programmer based his design on his own discretion.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="17" relname="conjunction">  He 
was familiar with guidelines</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="17" relname="conjunction"> and felt that this would fit the bill.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="19" relname="span">  I am not knocking the 
programmer</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="9" relname="evidence"> (he really is very talented and just made an error in judgement...</segment>
    <segment id="27" parent="9" relname="evidence">and he 
was probably pressed for time), </segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="21" relname="span"> but I see that not applying usability concepts to the little 
things can lead to big problems.</segment>
